<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BEAUTIFUL SWIMMERS: Watermen, Crabs and the Chesapeake Bay by William Warner, 
illustrated by Consuelo Hanks (Little, Brown: $11.95.; 304 pp.). Warner 
received the Pulitzer Prize for this lyrical, evocative study of the blue crab 
and the people who trap and prepare it.Warner's gracefully written prose 
conveys his enchantment with the vast estuary, " . . . an intimate place where 
land and water intertwine in infinite varieties of mood and pattern." He 
respectfully recounts the back-breaking labor the watermen endure to supply 
diners with this elusive delicacy. But Warner sounds an ominous note in the new 
afterword. Overfishing, pollution and the increasing population of the coastal 
regions have taken their toll on the crab population and the Bay itself: "You 
look hard at the water and sometimes it seems like it's getting a little old 
and tired, a little messy. Simple as that if anyone cares to notice." 
</P>
