<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WINE LIST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Dan Berger 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When the new Mortons opened, virtually every wine in the place was overpriced. 
But recently, prices were reduced almost across the board.What had been a steep 
$40 for 1990 Sonoma-Cutrer "Les Pierres" Chardonnay now is an OK $35; what had 
been an excessive $48 for 1990 Matanzas Creek Merlot is now an almost fair $40. 
</P>
<P>
 Still, this list is pretty unexciting. The California white wine "selection" 
is 18 Chardonnays and one Sauvignon Blanc -- and it's made like a Chardonnay 
(1992 Matanzas Creek, a bargain at $18). The domestic red list is almost all 
weighty Cabernet Sauvignons. 
</P>
<P>
 Of the whites, two great wines at fair prices are 1991 Sancerre from Comte La 
Fond, $28, and the best buy, 1992 Poggio Alle Gazze, a Sauvignon Blanc from the 
Tuscan estate of Lodovico Antinori, $20. 
</P>
<P>
 Of the red wines, the excellent 1991 Acacia Pinot Noir, $25, and the powerful 
1990 Chianti Classico "Peppoli" from Piero Antinori, $27, are both excellent 
choices. Dan Berger 
</P>
</TEXT>
