<P>
 HIDING OUT: It sounds like hype, but apparently it's true: Rapper Jazz Lee 
Alston is having to work on her debut album for American Records in a secret 
location because she's living in fear of a murderer whose crime she witnessed.  
</P>
<P>
 Alston was present when her cousin was shot to death in December, 1992, in New 
York.The killer is still at large. The incident, in fact, inspired Alston's 
song "Love . . . Never That," which was included in the American-distributed 
"Seattle . . . the Dark Side," an anthology of Northwest rap put together by 
Sir Mix-a-Lot. 
</P>
<P>
 The problem now is how to promote Alston's career without drawing the 
attention of a killer whom she could potentially help convict.  
</P>
<P>
 "I'll be out there promoting the album like any first-time artist," she 
promises. 
