<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITICS' PICKS: 'THE INDIAN RUNNER' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sean Penn's 1991 writing and directing debut is a psychodrama so intensely 
personal that it is difficult to read or even experience as anything more than 
a not-quite-veiled commentary on his own life. Based loosely on Bruce 
Springsteen's brooding song "Highway Patrolman," it is a Vietnam-era parable of 
two Midwestern brothers -- the local sheriff (David Morse, left) and the local 
hell-raiser (Viggo Mortensen) -- dealing in their own ways with the collapse of 
their family. Although overly self-involved, Penn is surprisingly focused as a 
director (TMC Monday at 2:20 a.m.). Kenneth Turan 
</P>
