<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITICS' PICKS: 'THE GOOD WOMAN OF BANGKOK' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Michael Wilmington 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 One of the most powerful and memorable documentaries on prostitution. The 
entire film is an act of exposure, of both Aoi, a Thai prostitute, and the 
filmmaker, the Australian Dennis O'Rourke, who falls in love with her in the 
process of making the film.We're never allowed to step very far back, either 
from Aoi's hurt life or O'Rourke's increasing shame at his part in it. He 
offered her a rice farm for her participation in the film; the result of that 
offer forms this 1992 documentary's bleak coda. Those who denounce this movie 
for its displays of nudity or conversations about sex will have foolishly 
missed the point (Cinemax Thursday at 4:30 a.m.) Michael Wilmington 
</P>
