<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOM FRANDSEN; VETERAN LOS ANGELES TV HOST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tom Frandsen, the smooth-talking but affable TV host and newsman on the Los 
Angeles scene for nearly 40 years, has died. 
</P>
<P>
 A family spokesman said Frandsen died Friday of the complications of a stroke 
at Scripps Hospital in Encinitas.He had been living in retirement in nearby 
Rancho La Costa. 
</P>
<P>
 For many years, Frandsen's appearances were a fixture in Southern California 
living rooms.  
</P>
<P>
 He began at KNBC after graduating from the University of Notre Dame's Navy 
flier program after World War II. He wrote news and was host of an afternoon 
movie and talk show. 
</P>
<P>
 "Tom Frandsen FYI" became one of the highest-rated afternoon shows in the area 
but was eventually canceled to make room for a network talk show hosted by a 
new national talent -- Mike Wallace. 
</P>
<P>
 "The network wanted my slot," Frandsen told The Times in 1985, because of the 
additional revenue generated by a national program. "But I had a contract and 
they had to pay me -- and handsomely," he added with obvious satisfaction. 
</P>
<P>
 Frandsen moved to KHJ, where he became vice president of community affairs and 
editorial director. 
</P>
<P>
 Although he officially retired more than a decade ago, he continued for a time 
to host "Meet the Mayors," a 30-minute series of interviews with the mayors of 
Southland cities on Channel 9, and another public service program, "Government 
Scene." 
</P>
<P>
 Survivors include his wife, June, two sons and four grandchildren, who ask 
that donations in Frandsen's name be sent to the Shriners' Hospital for 
Crippled Children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
