<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL; COUGARS POUNCE ON DEMOCRATS EARLY, 5-3 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SMITH, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Before the start of the Jefferson-Crenshaw baseball game last week Democrat 
assistant coach Victor Hayes was more concerned about his starting pitcher's 
lack of preparation than the opponent. 
</P>
<P>
 Because the Jefferson team arrived late at Crenshaw, Gabriel Avila didn't have 
time for many warm-up pitches. 
</P>
<P>
 And Hayes' fear became reality. 
</P>
<P>
 The Cougars scored all of their runs in the first inning en route to a 5-2 win 
in an L.A. Invitational second-round game Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
 "Gabby had control problems in the first inning, but after that Crenshaw 
couldn't hit his curveball," Hayes said. "If he had gotten warmed up before the 
start of the game, we could've won." 
</P>
<P>
 Crenshaw assistant coach Herb McNeely agreed: "(Avila) had some control 
problems in the first inning and we were able to take advantage. Once he 
started throwing that off-speed pitch, he was in control." 
</P>
<P>
 Avila (0-2) scattered two hits over the last six innings, which included seven 
strikeouts and three walks. 
</P>
<P>
 Down 5-1, the Democrats closed the gap in the top of the sixth when first 
baseman Ramses Cobian, who walked before stealing second and third, scored on 
Crenshaw catcher Mark Sarria's errant pick-off throw to third. 
</P>
<P>
 Cougar pitcher Leslie Williams (1-0) walked the next two batters, then threw a 
wild pitch, advancing the runners to second and third and putting the tying run 
at the plate in Avila. 
</P>
<P>
 However, Avila struck out on five pitches. 
</P>
<P>
 "We had our chances in this game, we just didn't capitalize," Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
 But Crenshaw did, making the most of its opportunities in the first. 
</P>
<P>
 Sarria knocked a single past Jefferson short stop Juan Arellano to load the 
bases and Cougar first baseman Shaun Smith hit a three-run double to left 
field. 
</P>
<P>
 Crenshaw scored its other two runs when Jefferson second baseman Juan Rosales 
fielded a ground ball and made a bad throw to first, with runners on first and 
third. 
</P>
<P>
 Smith was two-for-three with three RBIs in the game. 
</P>
<P>
 Williams finished with a four-hitter, striking out six. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was very impressed with Leslie's performance," McNeely said. "He has had 
control problems in the past, but he is getting away from it." 
</P>
<P>
 Crenshaw 12, Jordan 4 -- Crenshaw second baseman Juan Orita went 
three-for-three with four RBIs in a second-round game of the L.A. Invitational 
last week at Crenshaw. 
</P>
<P>
 Shortstop Mike McNeely went three-for-five with two RBIs for the Cougars. 
Jordan's Ernie Gomez hit two singles and a double with two RBIs in a losing 
effort. 
</P>
<P>
 University 6, Washington 3 -- Pitcher Marcus Christophe helped his own cause 
going two-for-three with two RBIs, but the Generals lost a second-round game of 
the L.A. Invitational at University. Washington's Sherod Johnson went 
two-for-four with one RBI. 
</P>
<P>
 Washington 15, Van Nuys 4 -- Washington third baseman Joseph George was the 
ring leader of the Generals' hit parade, going two-for-four with two RBIs in a 
third-round game of the L.A. Invitational last week at Van Nuys. 
</P>
<P>
 Washington's Sherod Johnson was also two-for-four with one RBI. 
</P>
<P>
 Hollywood 7, Jordan 6 -- Tony Sanchez's bloop-single in the bottom of the 
eighth inning scored the winning run as Hollywood won a second-round game of 
the L.A. Invitational at Hollywood High last week. First baseman Ernie Gomez, 
who was one-for-four with two RBIs, hit a two-run homer in the fifth inning to 
give the Bulldogs a brief 5-4 lead. 
</P>
