<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: CENTRAL: DOWNTOWN; HOTEL OWNER FINED, MUST FIX BUILDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IRIS YOKOI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 For the second time in five years, the owner of a Skid Row hotel again pleaded 
no contest to slum charges and was ordered to pay $11,711 in fines, spend 200 
hours in community service and repair the building by May 26. 
</P>
<P>
 If Chung Chuan Wang fails to make the repairs at the Modoc Hotel by the 
deadline, he must spend 30 days under house arrest at the hotel at 819 S. Towne 
Ave. 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles Municipal Judge Barry Taylor also placed Wang and his company, the 
Chi Cha Corp., on three years' probation after Wang pleaded no contest March 17 
to 10 charges of fire, health and building and safety code violations. 
</P>
<P>
 The current charges stem from city Slum Housing Task Force inspections 
conducted on Oct. 21 and Nov. 1 at the two-story, 76-room brick hotel, which is 
across the street from 9th Street Elementary School. 
</P>
<P>
 Inspectors reportedly found exposed live electrical wires, defective heater 
vents, missing and inoperable smoke detectors, missing and broken windows and 
screens, vermin infestation, an open sewer, defective plumbing, trash and 
debris throughout the premises and damaged and deteriorated walls and ceilings. 
</P>
<P>
 Defense attorney Bernard Talmas contends that Wang has spent "a small fortune" 
fixing the building and said the tenants are to blame for many of the problems. 
 
</P>
<P>
 Wang was prosecuted by the city attorney's housing enforcement unit in 1989 
after inspectors found similar conditions at the Modoc during two visits that 
year. Wang pleaded no contest to 12 slum charges and was ordered to pay $13,138 
in fines and to repair the building. 
</P>
<P>
 Wang made those repairs, but not before violating his probation by failing to 
meet the court-imposed deadline, prosecutors said. He was subsequently ordered 
to pay additional fines and perform 1,500 hours of community service. 
</P>
<P>
 The hotel has also been the source of prostitution and other crimes that 
prompted another unit of the city attorney's office to file a red-light 
abatement lawsuit against Wang in June, 1992. In the two years before the 
lawsuit was filed, undercover vice officers from the Police Department's Newton 
Division made 19 arrests for prostitution at the hotel and investigated a 
number of other crimes, including burglary, robbery and assault with a deadly 
weapon. IRIS YOKOI 
</P>
</TEXT>
