<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: VENTURA; CITY COUNCIL TO FILL 19 OPENINGS ON PANELS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PEGGY Y. LEE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Ventura City Council on Monday is expected to appoint 19 residents to four 
advisory panels. 
</P>
<P>
 Residents will serve one to three-year terms on three committees: 
</P>
<P>
 * The five-member Arts and Cultural Affairs Committee makes recommendations 
about art-related issues, and works toward acquiring art and cultural grants. 
</P>
<P>
 * The five-member Tourism and Special Events Committee oversees the city's 
tourism efforts, including the Ventura Visitors and Convention Bureau. 
</P>
<P>
 * The five-member Historic Preservation Committee oversees landmarks and 
historic districts. 
</P>
<P>
 All three committees report to a fourth panel, the Community Affairs 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
 Frank Cavola, John Correa, Deborah Nelson, Richard Peterson, Devlin Raley, 
Wyndra Roche and Bob Swanson are expected to be appointed to the Community 
Affairs Commission. 
</P>
<P>
 Ursula Britton, Neil Demers-Grey, Karen Mayer, Ed Robbings and Roche are 
expected to be appointed to the arts committee. 
</P>
<P>
 Beverly Benton, Nancy Cloutier, Howard McElroy, Marilyn Woods and Raley are 
expected to be appointed to the tourism committee. 
</P>
<P>
 Robert Chianese, Nick Deitch, Carolyn Newman, Jo Rogers and Peterson are 
expected to be appointed to the historic preservation committee. 
</P>
<P>
 All decisions of the panels can be appealed to the City Council. 
</P>
<P>
 Three council members -- Gary Tuttle, Steve Bennett and Jack Tingstrom -- 
screened and interviewed applicants. They are scheduled to make their 
recommendations to the council Monday. PEGGY Y. LEE 
</P>
</TEXT>
